  "topic_id": "T06.01",
  "topic_name": "Heat and Thermal Expansion",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Heat is a form of energy that flows from a hotter body to a colder body. The SI unit of heat is Joule (J), though calorie is also used (1 calorie = 4.186 J). Heat is different from temperature: heat is the total thermal energy, while temperature measures how hot or cold something is. When heat is added to a substance, it can cause temperature change, state change, or expansion. Thermal expansion is the increase in size of a substance when heated. Solids expand in length (linear), area (superficial), and volume (cubical). Liquids and gases also expand when heated. Water has anomalous expansion - it contracts when heated from 0°C to 4°C and then expands.",
    "rules": [
      "Heat is a form of energy that flows from hot to cold.",
      "SI unit of heat is Joule; 1 calorie = 4.186 J",
      "Temperature measures how hot or cold an object is.",
      "Heat causes: temperature change, state change, or expansion.",
      "Thermal expansion: increase in size due to heating.",
      "Solids: linear, superficial, and cubical expansion.",
      "Gases expand more than liquids; liquids expand more than solids.",
      "Water has anomalous expansion (max density at 4°C).",
      "Applications: expansion gaps in railways, bimetallic strips."
    ]
  },
